{
  "texts": [
    "The hit rate decreased only modestly when both human hepatocyte transduction models were excluded, demonstrating the utility of using models in combination (Fig. 4g).",
    "Separately, we performed a transduction study in rhesus macaques and found that six of the seven liver MultiFunction capsids individually validated in human cells and in mice in vivo (Fig. 4d, Supplementary Fig.",
    "7) were more efficient than AAV9 at transducing the rhesus macaque liver when administered as a library (Fig. 4h; n = 2 rhesus macaques, BI152 was inadvertently excluded due to a library assembly error).",
    "The Fit4Function pipeline presents a significant conceptual and technological advance over prior AAV engineering studies, including those that leverage ML.",
    "Conventional in vivo selections use sequential rounds to narrow the focus of sequence exploration to a handful of top candidates, which may not have other traits required for translation to preclinical models and clinical trials."
  ]
}